82
00:07:16,620 --> 00:07:22,060
formation, which consisted of 100 or so fighters
surrounding and protecting a bomber.

83
00:07:22,060 --> 00:07:27,180
Bader led the wing on every raid and had 20½
confirmed enemy aircraft destroyed. He had

84
00:07:27,180 --> 00:07:33,310
a veil of invincibility but then one day the
unthinkable happened. Whilst dog fighting

85
00:07:33,310 --> 00:07:38,519
with some Messerschmitts, something hit his
aircraft. It must have been an enemy fighter

86
00:07:38,519 --> 00:07:43,529
as when he turned around the rest of the aircraft
was missing. He tried to get out of the cockpit

87
00:07:43,529 --> 00:07:49,000
but his metal leg was trapped. Luckily he
could unclip it. Having legs would have sent

88
00:07:49,000 --> 00:07:53,250
him down with the Spitfire but instead he
was parachuting down to France and was knocked

89
00:07:53,250 --> 00:07:57,920
unconscious on landing.
He was soon discovered by three German officers

90
00:07:57,920 --> 00:08:03,310
and was taken to a nearby hospital in Saint
Omer. He asked the Germans to recover his

91
00:08:03,310 --> 00:08:08,189
leg, which they did, but the leg was damaged
so he asked them to repair it, which they

92
00:08:08,189 --> 00:08:10,709
also did.
He knew that once he was transferred to a

93
00:08:10,709 --> 00:08:15,959
prison camp in Germany it would be extremely
difficult to escape. He enlisted the help

94
00:08:15,959 --> 00:08:20,639
of a French nurse at the hospital, who gave
him a note from a local French couple, saying

95
00:08:20,639 --> 00:08:24,360
their son would be waiting outside the hospital
gates between midnight and 2am each night

96
00:08:24,360 --> 00:08:30,410
to help him, if he managed to escape. When
it was announced he was being transferred

97
00:08:30,410 --> 00:08:35,750
to Germany the next day, that evening Bader
